Use numeral + percent sign — unless a percentage starts a sentence, in which case spell out the number and use the word “percent,” e.g., “The survey showed that 88% of people would rather hang out with Lil Bub than Anne Hathaway”; “Eighty-five percent of the staff voted for a pizza party” (exception: OWS terms  the 1 percent
and  the 99 percent
).

This is a collective noun that requires a singular verb, e.g., “staff is”;  staffers
(or  staff members
) takes a plural, e.g., “staffers are.”

,  tea partyers
(cap only when referring to a specific group, e.g.,  Tea Party Express
)

;  the DC area
(but in datelines just  WASHINGTON
)
